`IFormFile` buffers into memory by default — for large files, you need to **disable buffering** and **read the multipart stream manually**.

### Key steps

**1. Disable the request size limit and form buffering:**

```csharp
// Program.cs
builder.WebApplication.MapPost("/upload", HandleUpload)
    .DisableAntiforgery()
    .WithMetadata(new RequestSizeLimitAttribute(2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024)); // 2 GB

// Also set in Kestrel config:
builder.WebApplication.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024);
```

**2. Stream the multipart body directly to disk:**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;

async Task<IResult> HandleUpload(HttpContext ctx)
{
    var contentType = ctx.Request.ContentType ?? "";
    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(
        MediaTypeHeaderValue.Parse(contentType).Boundary).Value;

    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Missing boundary");

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, ctx.Request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var disposition)
            || !disposition.IsFileDisposition())
            continue;

        // Stream directly to disk — no memory buffering
        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName();
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        await using var fileStream = File.Create(savePath);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fileStream);
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete");
}
```

### Why this works

| | `IFormFile` | `MultipartReader` |
|---|---|---|
| Memory | Buffers entire file | Streams in small chunks |
| 2 GB file | OOM crash | ~80 KB memory overhead |

### Don't forget

- **Disable form value count/size limits** if also reading form fields:
  ```csharp
  builder.Services.Configure<FormOptions>(o => {
      o.MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024;
  });
  ```
- **Validate the file** (size, type, name) before writing — never trust the client-supplied filename.
- If fronted by **Nginx/IIS**, raise their upload limits too (`client_max_body_size` / `maxAllowedContentLength`).
